President Obama has announced his intention to nominate Robert M. McDowell for another term at the Federal Communications Commission (FCC). McDowell has been a commissioner at the FCC since 2006, working on American communications policy in areas such as wireless, media, and the internet. He has also been involved in creating rules for wireless auctions, establishing a framework for unlicensed use of TV "white spaces" spectrum, and reviewing public interest benefits in proposed corporate mergers. McDowell has approximately sixteen years of private sector experience in the communications industry and is a graduate of Duke University and the Marshall-Wythe School of Law at the College of William and Mary. He is admitted to practice law before various courts, including the U.S. Supreme Court.